<h2 id="Problem-Statement">Problem Statement<a class="anchor-link" href="#Problem-Statement">¶</a></h2><p>Replication of the recommendation engines used by almost all e-commerce websites like Flipkart, Amazone etc. Creating a recommendation system that gives results for a certain user's preference and choice in fashion or clothing, The model must be easy to scale.</p>

</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing text_cell rendered"><div class="prompt input_prompt">
</div><div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<h1 id="Image-similarity-for-product-recommendation.">Image similarity for product recommendation.<a class="anchor-link" href="#Image-similarity-for-product-recommendation.">¶</a></h1>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing text_cell rendered"><div class="prompt input_prompt">
</div><div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<p>Online shopping websites always suggest items similar to the ones you have browsed and sometimes even items that can go with it. This notebook is a basic replication of the product recommendations using cosine image similarity. This topic falls majorly in the domain of Recommendation sytems, and I have a whole notebook dedicated to the topic. <a href="https://www.kaggle.com/niharika41298/recommendation-systems-in-a-nutshell">Check it out!</a></p>
<p><img src="https://1030z2bnst92zo6j523feq9e-wpengine.netdna-ssl.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/02/product-recommendations-hero.png" alt="Image"></p>

</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing text_cell rendered"><div class="prompt input_prompt">
</div><div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<h1 id="Dash-User-Interface">Dash User Interface<a class="anchor-link" href="#Dash-User-Interface">¶</a></h1><ul>
<li>Dash is basically a platform by the renowned Plotly library,which many data scientists use as a User Interface.</li>
<li>Dash uses Flask as the base framework and creates a web application where data scientists and analysts can display visualizations, text or any such asset. Dash is completely in Python so you do not have to worry about learning JavaScript. It is the nearest equivalent of the R Shiny platform.</li>
<li>Here is the static application for product recommendations that uses the vgg16 model to get recommendations.</li>
</ul>
<p>(Click on the below image)</p>
<p><a href="https://productrecom-n.herokuapp.com/"><img src="data:image/png;base64," alt="image.png"></a></p>

</div>
</div>
</div>

<span class="kn">import</span> <span class="nn">os</span>

<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<h1 id="Creating-a-Web-Application-using-Plotly-Dash">Creating a Web Application using Plotly-Dash<a class="anchor-link" href="#Creating-a-Web-Application-using-Plotly-Dash">¶</a></h1>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing text_cell rendered"><div class="prompt input_prompt">
</div><div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<p>There are a lot of ways to create web applications, the traditional ones being good old HTML and CSS. But, creating a web application that displays visualizations and also allows real-time interaction without using any javascript seemed nearly impossible.
On researching a bit, I found Dash. Dash was developed by plotly for creating easier dashboards with interactive graphs. The best part is that it mainly uses Python. Some designing needs to be done using bootstrap and CSS, but majority of the work is done in python.</p>

</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing text_cell rendered"><div class="prompt input_prompt">
</div><div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<h2 id="Problem-Statement">Problem Statement<a class="anchor-link" href="#Problem-Statement">¶</a></h2>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing text_cell rendered"><div class="prompt input_prompt">
</div><div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<p>Develop a User Interface for Content based filtering recommendation model for the good reads books dataset. The Interface must be a web application and should allow interactive graphs.</p>

</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing text_cell rendered"><div class="prompt input_prompt">
</div><div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<h2 id="Implementation">Implementation<a class="anchor-link" href="#Implementation">¶</a></h2>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing text_cell rendered"><div class="prompt input_prompt">
</div><div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<p>First step,Installation.</p>
<p>Steps:
->>pip install dash 
->>pip install dash_bootstrap_components</p>

</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing text_cell rendered"><div class="prompt input_prompt">
</div><div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<p>After the installation, dash provides sample layout programs on the website. Running those helps in understanding the environment and syntax.</p>

</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing text_cell rendered"><div class="prompt input_prompt">
</div><div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<h2 id="Design">Design<a class="anchor-link" href="#Design">¶</a></h2><p>Designing is something I have always struggled with. After looking at some applications for inspiration, I figured a sidebar would look great in the recommendation system. Also, there is a practice of displaying the most popular items in a lot of recommendation systems. After a rough sketch, I was sure what I wanted in my User Interface.</p>

</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing text_cell rendered"><div class="prompt input_prompt">
</div><div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<p>Sidebars look elegant in many UIs.</p>
<p><img src="https://media.nngroup.com/media/editor/2018/09/06/spotify_yourdailymixes.png" alt="Sidebar"></p>

</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing text_cell rendered"><div class="prompt input_prompt">
</div><div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<p>On searching, I found the base bootstrap code for a sidebar. As I had never worked with bootstrap, the code was a bit intimidating.
After a few runs,I figured out the code and started implementation of my project.</p>
<p><a href="#https://dash-bootstrap-components.opensource.faculty.ai/examples/simple-sidebar/">Dash sidebar code</a></p>

</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing text_cell rendered"><div class="prompt input_prompt">
</div><div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<h2 id="Deciding-color-scheme">Deciding color scheme<a class="anchor-link" href="#Deciding-color-scheme">¶</a></h2><p>I was familiar with the 6:3:1 color scheme.But, the colors needed to be decided. Dark theme looks very cool, but I needed three colors. A dark bluish black, white and blue was decided.</p>

</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing text_cell rendered"><div class="prompt input_prompt">
</div><div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<h2 id="Adding-graphs-and-recommendations">Adding graphs and recommendations<a class="anchor-link" href="#Adding-graphs-and-recommendations">¶</a></h2>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing text_cell rendered"><div class="prompt input_prompt">
</div><div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<p>Adding static graphs was simple, just create plotly figures and assign them to variables with ids and declare the ids in the layout.
But, adding interactive recommendations was tough.</p>

</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing text_cell rendered"><div class="prompt input_prompt">
</div><div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<p>Plotly Dash documentation explains callbacks for interactive graphs.
Recommendation system was imported as a module and a function was called when a title was selected by the user for getting recommendations.</p>

</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing text_cell rendered"><div class="prompt input_prompt">
</div><div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<h2 id="Moods">Moods<a class="anchor-link" href="#Moods">¶</a></h2><p>A lot of recommendation engines also had mood based recommendations, so I added 4 categories- Romantic, Mystery, Thriller and Fiction for displaying randomly shuffled recommendations on the basis of the chosen mood.</p>

</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing text_cell rendered"><div class="prompt input_prompt">
</div><div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<p>I know I should have taken screenshots while implementation but it slipped completely.</p>

</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing text_cell rendered"><div class="prompt input_prompt">
</div><div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<h1 id="Final-implementation">Final implementation<a class="anchor-link" href="#Final-implementation">¶</a></h1>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing text_cell rendered"><div class="prompt input_prompt">
</div><div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<p>Here is how the web app looks:</p>
<p><img src="data:image/png;base64," alt="image.png"></p>

</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing text_cell rendered"><div class="prompt input_prompt">
</div><div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<p><img src="data:image/png;base64," alt="image.png"></p>

</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing text_cell rendered"><div class="prompt input_prompt">
</div><div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<p>The code can be found in the github repo: <a href="#https://github.com/niharika412/dash-app">DASH APP</a></p>

</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing text_cell rendered"><div class="prompt input_prompt">
</div><div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<p>I tried deploying the application on heroku but memory limit exceeds and the application crashes. I am now looking at other servers for deployment. Although dash claims that apps can only be deployed on heroku as of now.
There is a lot of scope for improvement but this is just the basic model.</p>

</div>
</div>
</div>
